      "content": "### 2) SAR reasoning (why these features affect CYP2D6 inhibition)\n- **CYP2D6 strongly prefers a protonated basic N** that can form an ionic interaction with the active-site acidic residue (commonly Asp301). A **tertiary amine** in a rigid scaffold is very likely protonated at pH 7.4 and well-positioned for this interaction.\n- **Two phenyl rings** provide substantial **lipophilic surface and \u03c0-stacking/hydrophobic contacts** in the CYP2D6 binding pocket, increasing binding affinity and thus inhibitory potential.\n- The **rigid bicyclic amine** reduces conformational entropy penalty on binding and can mimic known high-affinity CYP2D6 ligands that present a fixed distance between the cationic center and aromatic moieties.\n- The **carbamate** can modulate polarity but does not remove the key pharmacophore (cationic N + aromatic bulk). It may add an extra H-bond acceptor that can contribute to binding orientation.",
